explanation: sysconf — need the function prototype to confirm parameter and return types and whether any pointer is involved (MISRA pointer/const rules apply only if pointers are used). If sysconf took or returned pointers or used const-qualified pointer parameters, that could affect the analysis. _SC_NPROCESSORS_ONLN, _SC_NPROC_ONLN — these macros/constants are the arguments passed to sysconf; confirm they are integer macros (not pointer macros) so no pointer/const issues arise from their use. HAVE_SYSCONF, HAS_DECL__SC_NPROCESSORS_ONLN, HAS_DECL__SC_NPROC_ONLN — preprocessor feature-test macros control whether the sysconf-based code is compiled at all; the analysis must know which branches are active to decide if any pointer usage exists in the compiled code. Knowing these symbols lets the next analyzer determine whether any pointer-to-const rules are relevant for this function (the function itself contains no pointers unless sysconf or those macros introduce pointer usage).
